~ The ADR proper.

@h1 ADR @adr.number — @adr.title h1@

*Status*: @adr.status · *Date*: @adr.date · *Authors*: @adr.authors

@h2 Context h2@

Our documentation has outgrown Markdown. Citations are increasingly
informal, cross-references rot when sections move, and we now
maintain three duplicate tables of contents across the handbook,
the website, and the chapter PDFs.

We need a markup language that lets us treat structure as data —
so the same chapter list drives the TOC, the navigation, and the
chapter bodies — and that supports an argument-map citation pattern
without forcing every reference into a footnote.

@h2 Options considered h2@

@table |schema name, pros, cons| |from @options|
table@

@h2 Decision h2@

We adopt Wit. The argument-map citation pattern alone justifies the
switch; the self-organising document layer (data drives content) is
a substantial bonus for our multi-author manual.

We commit to the v0.1.0 release and accept the smaller-community
risk in exchange for the ergonomic gains.

@h2 Consequences h2@

@info
Authors will need a brief onboarding. The witlang/skill package
ships a Claude Code skill that downstream agents and contributors
can use to write idiomatic Wit.
info@

@warn
Editor support is currently limited to VS Code. Contributors using
other editors will lack syntax highlighting and live errors until
we ship plugins for them. Planned: 2026-Q3.
warn@

The legacy Markdown handbook stays where it is for now. New
chapters will be authored in Wit; we'll migrate existing chapters
opportunistically.
